		<summary type="html">&lt;table style=&quot;margin:0 3px 3px; width:100%; text-align:left; background-color:transparent; border-collapse: collapse;&quot;&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;padding:0 0.9em 0 0;&quot;&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/File:Michael_Ancher_-_Chief_lifeboatman_Lars_Kruse_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg&quot; class=&quot;image&quot; title=&quot;Lars Kruse&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Lars Kruse&quot; src=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Michael_Ancher_-_Chief_lifeboatman_Lars_Kruse_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/300px-Michael_Ancher_-_Chief_lifeboatman_Lars_Kruse_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg&quot; width=&quot;300&quot; height=&quot;362&quot; srcset=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Michael_Ancher_-_Chief_lifeboatman_Lars_Kruse_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/450px-Michael_Ancher_-_Chief_lifeboatman_Lars_Kruse_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Michael_Ancher_-_Chief_lifeboatman_Lars_Kruse_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/600px-Michael_Ancher_-_Chief_lifeboatman_Lars_Kruse_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg 2x&quot; data-file-width=&quot;2772&quot; data-file-height=&quot;3342&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=&quot;padding:0 6px 0 0&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Lars_Kruse&quot; title=&quot;Lars Kruse&quot;&gt;Lars Kruse&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/b&gt; (1828–1894) was a &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Fisherman&quot; title=&quot;Fisherman&quot;&gt;fisherman&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Skagen&quot; title=&quot;Skagen&quot;&gt;Skagen&lt;/a&gt; in the far north of &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Jutland&quot; title=&quot;Jutland&quot;&gt;Jutland&lt;/a&gt;, Denmark, who was credited with saving over 200 lives. In one case, on 27 December 1862, he rescued much of the crew of the Swedish &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Brig&quot; title=&quot;Brig&quot;&gt;brig&lt;/a&gt; &lt;i&gt;Daphne&lt;/i&gt; when it was stranded during a storm. Kruse also gained fame through his portraits, painted by &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Michael_Ancher&quot; title=&quot;Michael Ancher&quot;&gt;Michael Ancher&lt;/a&gt;, and an account of his mistreatment written by &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Holger_Drachmann&quot; title=&quot;Holger Drachmann&quot;&gt;Holger Drachmann&lt;/a&gt; in a mixture of poems and prose.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;small&gt;Painting: &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Michael_Ancher&quot; title=&quot;Michael Ancher&quot;&gt;Michael Ancher&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
